WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:09.100
You know, usually when we talk about a medical diagnosis, there is this deep, almost unconscious expectation of precision.

00:09.460 --> 00:11.680
Oh, absolutely. We want it to be clean.

00:11.920 --> 00:14.120
Right. We want it to feel like engineering.

00:14.300 --> 00:18.560
So imagine you fall off a ladder, you break your arm, and you go to the hospital.

00:18.860 --> 00:23.740
You're sitting in that cold room with the plastic chairs, smelling the antiseptic.

00:23.800 --> 00:26.140
I can picture it. It's not a great place to be.

00:26.300 --> 00:27.360
No, it's awful.

00:27.360 --> 00:36.440
Yeah. But eventually, the doctor puts your x-ray up on the light board, and there is that jagged, glowing white line across the bone.

00:36.560 --> 00:36.860
Yeah.

00:37.040 --> 00:41.940
The doctor just points a pen at it and says, you know, there it is. That is the problem.

00:42.000 --> 00:45.880
And honestly, it is incredibly comforting in a strange way.

00:46.100 --> 00:48.660
It really is. Because it's binary.

00:48.940 --> 00:53.060
Exactly. Broken or not broken, it is undeniably visible.

00:53.060 --> 01:01.860
The ambiguity of your pain is suddenly cleanly categorized into a physical object you can literally point to.

01:01.980 --> 01:03.540
A completely clean distinction.

01:03.880 --> 01:11.400
And I think we carry that desire for a clean binary snapshot into almost every other aspect of our lives.

01:11.460 --> 01:12.160
Oh, without a doubt.

01:12.380 --> 01:15.120
But then you step into the world of human identity.

01:15.120 --> 01:20.840
You step into the mechanics of consciousness or, you know, how we actually move through time.

01:21.140 --> 01:24.180
And suddenly, that x-ray machine is completely useless.

01:24.440 --> 01:25.340
Totally useless.

01:25.960 --> 01:28.800
Yet, we still crave those snapshots, don't we?

01:29.060 --> 01:38.300
I mean, we want a driver's license or a credit score or even a personality test to do the exact same thing that the medical scan does.

01:38.300 --> 01:43.380
We want to point to a piece of paper and say, ah, there I am. That static picture is me.

01:43.820 --> 01:48.720
Right. Which, as we're going to see today, is entirely a cognitive illusion.

01:49.060 --> 01:54.940
Because your true identity, I mean, structurally speaking, isn't that frozen snapshot at all?

01:55.160 --> 01:55.960
No, it's not.

01:56.200 --> 02:02.740
If we go back to your broken arm, the reality of that arm isn't the single frame of the x-ray.

02:02.740 --> 02:10.920
The reality is the entire messy, irreversible history of how that specific bone grew over decades.

02:11.060 --> 02:13.860
Like the childhood diet, the genetics, all of it.

02:13.940 --> 02:14.500
Exactly.

02:14.920 --> 02:21.700
The exact velocity and angle at which it fractured, the biological cascade of how it healed over months,

02:21.720 --> 02:28.320
and even every single step you chose to take or are favored slightly differently for the rest of your life because of that injury.

02:28.320 --> 02:33.460
It's a living, breathing, irreversible log of events.

02:33.740 --> 02:34.280
It is.

02:34.460 --> 02:44.560
And the overarching thesis we are exploring in this deep dive today is that the moment we try to freeze that log into a static snapshot,

02:45.320 --> 02:49.940
the moment we try to reduce a human being to an x-ray or a data point,

02:50.180 --> 02:53.940
we actually destroy the very structural integrity that makes you you.

02:53.940 --> 02:57.780
And that structural destruction isn't just a philosophical metaphor.

02:58.460 --> 03:06.400
According to the incredibly dense research we are unpacking today, it is a literal mathematical crisis.

03:06.540 --> 03:10.640
A crisis that is tearing apart our digital and economic systems right now.

03:10.720 --> 03:11.960
Yes, exactly.

03:12.160 --> 03:14.640
Which brings us to the mission for this deep dive.

03:15.300 --> 03:22.740
Today, we are immersing ourselves in a truly radical, mathematically rigorous paper published in March 2026.

03:22.740 --> 03:25.700
A very recent, very heavy piece of work.

03:25.860 --> 03:26.460
Very heavy.

03:26.860 --> 03:30.700
The author goes by the handle Fliction, or Fliction, depending on how you pronounce it.

03:30.780 --> 03:30.980
Yeah.

03:31.080 --> 03:38.020
And the paper is titled Process, Projection, and Power Toward a Unified Ontology of Choice, Causality, and Value.

03:38.160 --> 03:38.860
Go ahead and mouthful.

03:38.980 --> 03:39.300
It is.

03:39.640 --> 03:46.060
And alongside that, we will be deeply exploring the core theorems of an interconnected framework known as the compiled self.

03:46.320 --> 03:50.840
I just have to say, it is a staggering amount of material to synthesize.

03:50.840 --> 03:54.980
The ambition of this author is off the charts.

03:55.580 --> 04:15.700
They are attempting to build a single, cohesive, formal, mathematical architecture that connects the deepest physical mysteries of time straight up through the cognitive experience of human consciousness and all the way out into the macroeconomics of global coordination.

04:15.700 --> 04:20.180
It's basically a theory of everything, but applied to human identity.

04:20.660 --> 04:21.220
Exactly.

04:21.580 --> 04:25.760
So our goal today is to decode this architecture for you, the listener.

04:26.040 --> 04:29.540
We're going to look under the hood of reality itself.

04:30.020 --> 04:35.500
We'll explore why classical physics fails to explain what it feels like to be alive.

04:35.600 --> 04:37.000
A huge topic on its own.

04:37.000 --> 04:37.600
For sure.

04:37.920 --> 04:54.920
We'll also cover how human identity is mathematically constructed from moment to moment, and why modern algorithms, the ones currently running our society, are mathematically guaranteed to degrade that identity by flattening it into what the paper calls one-dimensional slop.

04:55.260 --> 04:57.900
We are also going to look at the geometry of how you make choices.

04:58.280 --> 05:05.120
And perhaps most importantly, we will examine the highly technical blueprint the author proposes at the end of the paper.

05:05.120 --> 05:06.760
The cure, basically.

05:07.020 --> 05:07.200
Right.

05:07.280 --> 05:13.720
A new computational grammar designed to save complex digital and economic systems from total collapse.

05:14.120 --> 05:16.220
It is a massive intellectual journey.

05:16.860 --> 05:23.820
But before we really get into the mechanics of the math and the philosophy, I want to take a moment to be completely transparent with you.

05:24.140 --> 05:26.100
Yeah, we need a quick disclaimer here.

05:26.100 --> 05:26.500
Right.

05:26.780 --> 05:33.740
Because the sources we are working from today dive fearlessly into some incredibly heavy systemic critiques.

05:33.740 --> 05:44.100
The text aggressively analyzes capitalism, the consolidation of corporate power, economic extraction, and institutional decay.

05:44.680 --> 05:49.120
It uses these economic models to literally prove its mathematical points.

05:49.880 --> 05:54.520
The systemic analysis is woven directly into the topology of the math.

05:55.040 --> 06:00.100
The author does not separate the physics of time from the realities of modern labor.

06:00.100 --> 06:00.700
Exactly.

06:01.840 --> 06:09.900
Because of that, I need to explicitly state that our mission today is to impartially report on the math and the frameworks provided in these texts.

06:10.200 --> 06:14.940
We are not endorsing any political, economic, or ideological viewpoints.

06:15.060 --> 06:17.780
We are not taking sides on the paper systemic critiques.

06:17.780 --> 06:18.500
Right.

06:18.980 --> 06:30.840
We are simply acting as your guides, exploring the profound and honestly mind-bending concepts contained in this text to see what we can learn from the architecture it proposes.

06:31.280 --> 06:42.520
And if we are going to understand this new architecture, this math of the compiled self, we have to start by completely demolishing our default assumptions about how the universe works.

06:42.720 --> 06:45.520
We have to start at the very bottom layer of reality.

06:45.640 --> 06:46.200
We do.

06:46.200 --> 06:46.860
Let's do it.

06:46.980 --> 06:47.000
Let's do it.

06:47.000 --> 06:55.980
So, in classical science, basically, since the Enlightenment and Isaac Newton, we have treated reality as being fundamentally made up of static objects.

06:56.240 --> 06:56.520
Right.

06:56.520 --> 07:02.420
We look around and we think the universe is a giant container, and inside that container are things.

07:03.000 --> 07:06.240
Particles, planets, chairs, people, dollars.

07:06.780 --> 07:11.580
And then, as a secondary phenomenon, those things occasionally move or change state.

07:11.940 --> 07:15.420
This is what fliction refers to as an ontology of being.

07:15.420 --> 07:17.480
Okay, unpack that term for us.

07:17.540 --> 07:21.540
Well, ontology is just the philosophical study of what actually exists.

07:21.860 --> 07:31.760
So, an ontology of being is the core assumption that static stuff matter, objects, isolated entities, is the primary ingredient of reality.

07:31.760 --> 07:34.040
I always think of it like a game of pool.

07:34.040 --> 07:45.060
In classical science, we treat the universe like a set of billiard balls sitting motionless on a green felt table, just waiting for the cue ball to strike them.

07:45.320 --> 07:46.280
That's a great visual.

07:46.280 --> 07:50.860
The being, the static ball, is the default state of the universe.

07:51.600 --> 07:58.580
The doing the movement across the table is just an accidental property that happens to the being when force is applied.

07:58.840 --> 08:02.720
That is the perfect way to visualize the classical mindset.

08:03.400 --> 08:07.060
But Fliction's paper completely inverts that paradigm.

08:07.620 --> 08:12.460
It argues that classical science is looking at reality entirely backward.

08:12.820 --> 08:13.380
Backward how?

08:13.380 --> 08:17.820
The paper proposes what it calls an ontology of becoming.

08:19.320 --> 08:29.460
In this framework, transitions, choices, processes, the irreversible changes from one state to another, those are not accidents happening to static objects.

08:29.920 --> 08:34.020
The transitions are the actual fundamental building blocks of reality.

08:34.280 --> 08:34.740
Okay, wait.

08:34.820 --> 08:36.280
So, the doing is the default?

08:36.500 --> 08:39.560
The doing is the only fundamental reality.

08:39.560 --> 08:44.460
Everything we think of as a static object is actually just a secondary projection.

08:44.820 --> 08:45.340
Like a shadow.

08:45.820 --> 08:46.360
Exactly.

08:46.640 --> 08:51.020
It's a temporary shadow cast by an underlying continuous process.

08:51.480 --> 08:54.500
To use your analogy, there are no billiard balls.

08:54.840 --> 08:55.340
Wait, really?

08:55.600 --> 08:55.900
None.

08:56.120 --> 08:56.600
None.

08:56.600 --> 09:00.540
There is only the continuous process of momentum and collision.

09:00.540 --> 09:10.100
And when that process loops tightly enough in a localized area, it creates the temporary localized illusion of a solid sphere.

09:10.440 --> 09:10.840
Oh, wow.

09:11.240 --> 09:17.120
You, as a human being, are not a static object that occasionally makes a choice.

09:17.380 --> 09:24.020
You are the continuous process of making choices which generates the temporary interface of a person.

09:24.020 --> 09:26.520
That is a total ontological flip.

09:26.640 --> 09:31.620
It takes a second for the brain to even process that because our language is so noun heavy.

09:31.980 --> 09:32.600
Oh, definitely.

09:33.000 --> 09:34.240
We're wired for nouns.

09:34.480 --> 09:37.680
We want to be nouns, but the paper says we are verbs.

09:38.180 --> 09:45.840
And to see why this radical flip is mathematically necessary, we have to look at one of the biggest failures in modern science.

09:46.660 --> 09:50.580
We have to talk about David Chalmers and the hard problem of consciousness.

09:50.580 --> 09:55.580
Because this is exactly where the billiard ball model of the universe completely breaks down.

09:55.980 --> 09:56.580
It really is.

09:56.980 --> 10:00.360
It's the ultimate roadblock for the ontology of being.

10:01.340 --> 10:10.820
For anyone who hasn't encountered this concept, the philosopher David Chalmers formulated the hard problem of consciousness in the 1990s.

10:11.100 --> 10:14.300
And it asks a deceptively simple question.

10:14.940 --> 10:18.640
How does physical matter create subjective experience?

10:18.800 --> 10:19.140
Right.

10:19.140 --> 10:25.660
Because if the universe is just static things bumping into each other, where does the feeling come from?

10:26.280 --> 10:30.140
We can map the neural pathways of the human brain perfectly.

10:30.440 --> 10:31.860
We can look at the x-ray.

10:32.100 --> 10:35.380
We can see the electrical signals jumping across the synapses.

10:35.740 --> 10:38.800
We can map the exact chemistry of serotonin and dopamine.

10:38.800 --> 10:39.600
Exactly.

10:40.240 --> 10:50.660
But none of that physical, mechanical interaction tells us why it feels like something to see the color red or to taste a strawberry or to feel grief.

10:50.740 --> 10:51.240
Exactly.

10:51.520 --> 10:57.400
The physics gives us the blind mechanics, but it completely fails to account for the first-person perspective.

10:58.060 --> 11:01.720
The rich, qualitative, internal experience of being alive.

11:01.720 --> 11:02.220
Right.

11:02.520 --> 11:08.860
Physics can explain how the eye processes a wavelength of light, which is what Chalmers calls the easy problem.

11:08.860 --> 11:11.660
Which isn't actually easy, but comparatively.

11:12.080 --> 11:12.320
Right.

11:12.520 --> 11:13.080
Comparatively.

11:13.760 --> 11:16.700
But it cannot explain the experience of redness.

11:17.360 --> 11:18.780
That is the hard problem.

11:19.220 --> 11:24.780
And the text brings in the work of a systems theorist named Forrest Landry here, which I found fascinating.

11:26.060 --> 11:33.900
Landry argues that the reason traditional physics can't solve the hard problem is because of the foundational perspective from which physics is built.

11:33.900 --> 11:47.240
Yes. Landry points out that when we build physical models of the universe, whether it's Newtonian mechanics or Einstein's relativity, we construct them exclusively from a third-person perspective.

11:47.580 --> 11:48.580
We step outside of it.

11:48.660 --> 11:51.640
We step outside the universe to look at it as a whole.

11:51.900 --> 11:56.340
And when we do that, we create what physicists call the block universe.

11:56.760 --> 11:57.640
The block universe.

11:58.040 --> 11:58.320
Yeah.

11:58.320 --> 12:08.020
This is the idea that time isn't actually flowing, but that time is just another geometric dimension, exactly like length, width, or height.

12:08.180 --> 12:08.780
Precisely.

12:08.780 --> 12:24.160
In the mathematics of general relativity, every single moment in time, the Big Bang, the moment you were born, the present second, and the eventual heat death of the universe, it all exists simultaneously as a static four-dimensional block.

12:24.260 --> 12:25.540
It's all just there.

12:25.940 --> 12:27.020
It's all just there.

12:27.020 --> 12:36.660
In those physical equations, time is perfectly symmetric, you can run the math forward, or you can run the math backward, and the equations work exactly the same.

12:37.060 --> 12:40.860
There is no mathematical distinction between the past and the future.

12:41.420 --> 12:48.120
I always try to visualize the block universe like a digital movie file sitting on my computer's hard drive.

12:48.180 --> 12:49.200
Okay, I like that.

12:49.200 --> 12:57.200
The entire movie, from the opening credits to the end scene, exists simultaneously on the disk.

12:57.760 --> 13:04.680
The physics equations give us the progress bar at the bottom of the screen, and that progress bar is perfectly symmetric.

13:05.480 --> 13:12.800
As an observer outside the movie, I can drag my mounts and click to minute two, or I can click to minute 90.

13:12.800 --> 13:15.180
It's all equally accessible data.

13:15.240 --> 13:15.480
Right.

13:15.560 --> 13:19.360
That is the third-person block universe view of reality.

13:19.520 --> 13:28.940
It is a brilliant mathematical model for calculating planetary orbits, but it has a fatal flaw when it comes to human reality.

13:29.140 --> 13:33.260
Because that is absolutely not how you and I actually experience reality.

13:33.360 --> 13:33.720
It isn't.

13:33.780 --> 13:34.440
Not even close.

13:34.440 --> 13:41.080
No, we don't experience our lives as a symmetric progress bar where we can jump back to yesterday.

13:41.800 --> 13:46.020
We experience time as a relentless, moving laser.

13:46.820 --> 13:52.700
We are the playhead on the progress bar, reading exactly one frame of reality at a time.

13:52.760 --> 13:53.780
That's a great way to put it.

13:53.940 --> 13:54.640
The playhead.

13:55.040 --> 13:57.540
The first-person perspective is the playhead.

13:57.540 --> 14:05.460
As it moves, it leaves a trail of watched frames behind it, the fixed, irreversible past.

14:05.960 --> 14:11.540
And it looks forward into an unplayed buffer, the open, undetermined future.

14:12.260 --> 14:19.540
The block universe progress bar might be symmetric, but the playhead's journey is aggressively, violently asymmetric.

14:20.260 --> 14:21.600
It only goes in one direction.

14:21.600 --> 14:29.080
And classical science, because it only believes in the third-person block universe, has no explanation for the playhead.

14:29.280 --> 14:30.320
They just ignore it.

14:30.480 --> 14:39.940
In fact, many strict materialist physicists will argue that the feeling of, you know, the sensation of time passing is literally just a psychological illusion.

14:40.440 --> 14:49.000
They argue that the static progress bar is the objective reality, and your subjective feeling of the playhead moving is just a trick your brain is playing on you.

14:49.000 --> 14:53.360
Which feels incredibly insulting to my daily experience, frankly.

14:53.520 --> 14:54.200
Oh, absolutely.

14:54.560 --> 14:59.560
But here's where Flickshinian's paper introduces its radical solution to the hard problem.

15:00.440 --> 15:01.240
The paper says,

15:01.860 --> 15:03.840
No, the physicists have it backwards.

15:05.180 --> 15:10.020
The static block universe, the progress bar, is the mathematical abstraction.

15:10.780 --> 15:14.220
The moving playhead is the fundamental reality of the universe.

15:14.740 --> 15:17.420
This is the core of the ontology of becoming.

15:17.420 --> 15:23.580
The paper argues that consciousness isn't some magical, ethereal substance floating in your head.

15:23.780 --> 15:29.640
It isn't some emergent smoke that gets magically generated when brain cells get complex enough.

15:30.500 --> 15:35.780
Consciousness is the fundamental internal experience of temporal asymmetry.

15:35.980 --> 15:37.860
Let's slow down and really unpack that.

15:38.240 --> 15:41.560
Consciousness is the internal experience of temporal asymmetry.

15:41.560 --> 15:48.240
So going back to the playhead, consciousness is just the friction of that playhead moving forward.

15:48.920 --> 15:49.660
In a sense, yes.

15:49.900 --> 15:52.580
Think about what is actually happening at the present moment.

15:52.700 --> 15:54.380
You are standing at the edge of the present.

15:54.940 --> 15:59.200
In front of you is a space of multiple, undetermined, possible futures.

15:59.920 --> 16:01.100
You have to make a choice.

16:01.460 --> 16:08.640
The moment you make a choice, you collapse all those myriad possibilities into a single, fixed, irreversible historical fact.

16:08.640 --> 16:12.840
You take the fluid future and you forge it into the solid past.

16:13.440 --> 16:18.640
And that transition from possibility to fixed history is mathematically asymmetric.

16:19.380 --> 16:20.440
You can't undo it.

16:20.700 --> 16:21.040
Exactly.

16:21.320 --> 16:31.780
And what Fliction argues is that this physical collapse, this transition from many futures to one past, has an internal subjective aspect to it.

16:31.920 --> 16:34.120
That internal aspect is consciousness.

16:34.480 --> 16:34.740
Wow.

16:34.740 --> 16:43.000
Subjective experience is simply what it feels like from the inside to be the process that resolves possibilities into history.

16:43.240 --> 16:49.180
We are not static biological objects that somehow possess consciousness as a property.

16:49.480 --> 16:53.380
We are the active, irreversible process of time flowing.

16:53.600 --> 16:57.040
And the feeling of being alive is the sensation of that flow.

16:57.240 --> 16:57.500
Okay.

16:57.640 --> 16:59.820
My mind is already stretched to its limits.

16:59.820 --> 17:08.320
We have shifted from a universe made of static billiard balls to a universe made of pure process, transition, and flow.

17:08.520 --> 17:08.840
Yes.

17:09.080 --> 17:13.320
The problem of consciousness is solved by realizing we're the flow of time.

17:13.580 --> 17:17.860
But this immediately raises a huge, terrifying question for me.

17:17.920 --> 17:18.320
Which is?

17:18.320 --> 17:29.160
If reality is just this endless, continuous sequence of transitions, if there is no solid, static stuff at the bottom of it all, how do we not just dissolve into pure chaos?

17:29.160 --> 17:36.360
If I am not a physical object, but just a verb, how does a stable me exist at all?

17:36.680 --> 17:40.100
How do I wake up feeling like the same person I was yesterday?

17:40.100 --> 17:46.900
That is the exact tension that drives the entire second major section of the source material.

17:47.240 --> 18:03.100
If we throw out the comforting idea of a static soul locked in a jar, or the idea that your identity is just your physical body, especially since your biological cells are constantly dying and replacing themselves, what is human identity?

18:03.260 --> 18:03.440
Right.

18:03.520 --> 18:04.700
What is holding it together?

18:04.700 --> 18:05.380
Exactly.

18:05.900 --> 18:11.120
The paper introduces a formal, mathematically rigorous architecture to answer this.

18:11.420 --> 18:13.660
It is called the compiled self.

18:13.920 --> 18:14.940
The compiled self.

18:15.060 --> 18:16.780
I love the terminology here.

18:17.360 --> 18:21.920
It implies that identity isn't a pre-existing thing you were handed at birth.

18:22.500 --> 18:26.180
It is an ongoing, dynamically maintained abstraction.

18:26.740 --> 18:29.040
It is something you have to continuously compute.

18:29.240 --> 18:30.060
It is an achievement.

18:30.060 --> 18:41.520
Yes, and to prove why we need this incredibly specific mathematical architecture to maintain an identity, the paper actually starts by showing us what happens when an identity fails to compile.

18:41.960 --> 18:46.080
It shows us a massive structural failure in artificial intelligence.

18:46.460 --> 18:49.380
Yes, the Markov name generator experiment.

18:50.020 --> 18:55.560
The author uses this experiment as a beautiful, isolating proof of concept.

18:56.060 --> 18:57.860
Let's break down exactly what happened.

18:57.960 --> 18:58.420
Please do.

18:58.420 --> 19:04.000
The author built a relatively simple AI system based on a Markov chain.

19:04.700 --> 19:07.380
A Markov chain is essentially a probability engine.

19:08.080 --> 19:14.080
It looks at a current state and predicts the most likely next state based on historical training data.

19:14.700 --> 19:19.720
So in this case, the author trained it on English phonetic rules and historical names.

19:19.840 --> 19:20.180
Correct.

19:20.520 --> 19:26.240
The goal was to generate completely novel, unique names that had never existed before.

19:26.240 --> 19:35.720
The system would look at a letter, say T, and use probability to guess that H or R should come next and then guess the next vowel and so on.

19:35.800 --> 19:36.500
Okay, makes sense.

19:36.500 --> 19:40.940
And on a purely lexical level, the experiment was a massive success.

19:40.940 --> 19:43.640
Oh yeah, the names that spit out were fantastic.

19:44.200 --> 19:45.840
They sounded lexically plausible.

19:46.500 --> 19:52.140
They sounded like they could belong to real historical figures or characters in a high fantasy novel.

19:52.400 --> 19:54.940
Names like Fowler or Caelan or Vespera.

19:55.940 --> 19:57.520
They had a beautiful phonetic surface.

19:57.520 --> 20:02.420
But then the author took the experiment to the crucial second stage.

20:03.060 --> 20:14.680
They took these brand new phonetically unique names and fed them into a massive state-of-the-art large language model, a neural network with billions of parameters.

20:15.040 --> 20:17.000
Like the AIs everyone is using today.

20:17.120 --> 20:17.780
Exactly.

20:17.780 --> 20:28.640
And the author prompted the language model, here is a name, invent a backstory, a mythology, and a distinct personality for this individual.

20:29.180 --> 20:33.740
And the result was an absolute structural collapse.

20:33.880 --> 20:35.220
Complete semantic failure.

20:35.220 --> 20:49.560
No matter how cinetically unique the names were, no matter how different Fowler sounded from Caelan, the language model immediately collapsed their backstories into the exact same handful of generic, repetitive tropes.

20:49.640 --> 20:50.620
Every single time.

20:50.820 --> 20:56.980
Every single name became an ancient, wise sage living in the woods or a cyclical deity of nature and balance.

20:56.980 --> 21:05.420
The AI created lexical novelty on the surface, but when asked to generate an identity, it fell into a generic sinkhole.

21:05.840 --> 21:11.180
And the paper meticulously argues that this was not just a temporary glitch or a lack of training data.

21:11.380 --> 21:13.740
It was a mathematical inevitability.

21:14.060 --> 21:14.800
Why did it happen?

21:15.240 --> 21:19.060
Because the generated names lacked what Fliction calls history coupling.

21:19.420 --> 21:20.260
History coupling.

21:20.460 --> 21:21.500
Let's dig into that.

21:21.500 --> 21:28.480
When the Markov chain generated the word Thaler, each letter was chosen probabilistically in isolation.

21:29.540 --> 21:38.340
The A was chosen because it fit well after the Aish, but there was no deeper, continuous logic tying the entire name to a lived history.

21:38.940 --> 21:39.840
It was just math.

21:40.060 --> 21:41.060
Just surface math.

21:41.360 --> 21:44.740
The name had no physical or temporal constraints.

21:45.240 --> 21:47.380
It was a surface without a substrate.

21:47.380 --> 21:51.640
It's like generating a shadow without a physical object to cast the shadow.

21:51.860 --> 21:52.420
Exactly.

21:53.260 --> 22:01.560
So when the massive language model looks at that shadow and tries to interpret the person behind it, it finds nothing to grab onto.

22:01.940 --> 22:03.620
There is no historical friction.

22:03.940 --> 22:05.900
There are no underlying constraints.

22:06.380 --> 22:07.280
And without that.

22:07.360 --> 22:15.860
Without constraints to guide it, the massive probabilistic weight of the language model just defaults to the densest center of its training data.

22:15.860 --> 22:21.020
It defaults to the most generic, highly repeated archetypes of human myth.

22:21.480 --> 22:26.200
It hallucinates a generic average because the input has no sovereign uniqueness.

22:26.640 --> 22:32.400
So, if unconstrained generation isn't enough to create a distinct identity,

22:32.400 --> 22:39.100
if just making up a random string of letters or actions doesn't make a self-quoting,

22:40.620 --> 22:46.660
what is the actual mathematical requirement for an identity to exist and survive?

22:47.040 --> 22:49.440
This is where we get to the core of the paper.

22:50.100 --> 22:56.060
Fliction outlines the architecture of identity through four rigorous mathematical theorems.

22:56.060 --> 23:03.920
If you want to exist as a stable, compiled self, you must continuously satisfy these four conditions.

23:04.220 --> 23:05.220
Okay, let's go through them.

23:05.280 --> 23:07.120
The first one is the abstraction theorem.

23:07.280 --> 23:08.860
Let's unpack the abstraction theorem.

23:09.580 --> 23:15.200
The text states that a stable interface, a stable you that can be recognized and interacted with over time,

23:15.960 --> 23:21.360
only exists if a constraint functional enforces global coherence across your history.

23:21.720 --> 23:23.080
A constraint functional.

23:23.080 --> 23:29.140
In layman's terms, your identity is mathematically defined by the rules you refuse to break.

23:29.240 --> 23:30.040
Oh, that's interesting.

23:30.220 --> 23:34.080
The accumulated history of what you have done in the past acts as a rigid constraint

23:34.620 --> 23:38.660
on what you are mathematically allowed to do next if you wish to remain you.

23:39.040 --> 23:42.300
I have to admit, when I first read this, I wanted to push back aggressively.

23:42.380 --> 23:43.320
Oh, most people do.

23:43.580 --> 23:49.220
Because culturally, we are taught that true freedom means having infinite options.

23:49.220 --> 23:57.660
We think of our identity as this limitless potential, and constraints are just societal cages trapping the real me.

23:58.240 --> 24:04.540
If my identity is just an interface, hiding a bunch of contradictory chaotic impulses underneath,

24:05.120 --> 24:08.280
aren't constraints the enemy of my true self?

24:08.440 --> 24:11.420
It's a very intuitive, very human assumption.

24:11.420 --> 24:16.320
But the mathematics of complex systems proves the exact opposite.

24:16.660 --> 24:17.960
Let's look at it structurally.

24:18.740 --> 24:21.800
Imagine you are trying to build a massive skyscraper.

24:22.760 --> 24:26.460
The constraint functional is the physics beneath the architecture.

24:27.000 --> 24:34.880
The load-bearing steel beams, the poured concrete foundation, the strict laws of tension, compression, and gravity.

24:35.060 --> 24:36.340
Right, the stuff holding it out.

24:36.340 --> 24:41.420
If you suddenly decide that constraints are a cage, and you want your building to be infinitely free,

24:41.520 --> 24:42.060
what do you do?

24:42.140 --> 24:48.100
You remove the steel beams, you just start stacking glass panels and drywall on top of each other

24:48.100 --> 24:50.180
in any arbitrary shape you want.

24:50.660 --> 24:52.660
Does the building become infinitely free?

24:52.880 --> 24:55.340
No, it instantly shatters under its own weight.

24:55.800 --> 24:58.720
It ceases to be a building at all, becomes a pile of rubble.

24:58.960 --> 24:59.440
Exactly.

24:59.680 --> 25:03.040
So the constraints are not the cage trapping the building.

25:03.040 --> 25:08.200
The constraints are the bones that allow the building to exist in the first place.

25:08.720 --> 25:10.280
The constraints are the bones.

25:10.600 --> 25:11.380
I love that.

25:12.280 --> 25:18.020
Without them, any new action I take could arbitrarily contradict my past actions,

25:18.340 --> 25:24.240
and the coherent abstraction known as my personality would fracture into noise.

25:24.360 --> 25:24.700
Yes.

25:25.180 --> 25:28.940
I would be a completely different person from millisecond to millisecond.

25:29.420 --> 25:31.660
My family wouldn't recognize me.

25:31.660 --> 25:33.380
I wouldn't recognize myself.

25:34.100 --> 25:38.660
The constraints are what allow an abstraction to cohere over the span of a lifetime.

25:38.880 --> 25:40.400
That is the abstraction theorem.

25:40.660 --> 25:42.060
You must have structural bones.

25:42.420 --> 25:44.480
Which leads us directly to the second pillar.

25:45.100 --> 25:46.180
The substrate theorem.

25:46.840 --> 25:52.020
This theorem deals with the physical or digital medium that actually carries your identity.

25:52.340 --> 25:54.120
Because the math has to run on something.

25:54.120 --> 25:54.540
Right.

25:54.700 --> 25:58.940
And the substrate theorem states that whatever medium is hosting your compiled self,

25:59.540 --> 26:04.640
it must have the physical capacity to preserve your spectral signatures.

26:05.000 --> 26:06.020
Spectral signatures.

26:06.540 --> 26:11.100
We are moving from architecture into some heavy signal processing terminology here.

26:11.300 --> 26:15.580
We are, but it's vital for understanding how uniqueness survives.

26:15.960 --> 26:20.020
The paper uses Fourier transforms to explain this concept.

26:20.020 --> 26:21.160
Okay, let's pause.

26:22.180 --> 26:24.780
Walk me through a Fourier transform.

26:25.240 --> 26:30.560
I know it's a way to analyze waves, but how does it apply to human choices?

26:31.000 --> 26:31.940
Let's break it down.

26:32.360 --> 26:38.700
In mathematics, a Fourier transform is a tool that takes a very complex, messy signal,

26:38.960 --> 26:40.660
like the sound of a symphony orchestra,

26:40.660 --> 26:45.680
and breaks it apart into its fundamental continuous sine waves.

26:45.880 --> 26:46.120
Okay.

26:46.460 --> 26:52.160
It reveals the exact frequencies and amplitudes that combine to make that complex sound.

26:52.220 --> 26:54.860
So it finds the hidden rhythm inside the noise.

26:54.940 --> 26:55.460
Exactly.

26:55.460 --> 26:58.560
Now apply that to the continuous process of your life.

26:58.840 --> 27:00.860
Imagine tracking every choice you make.

27:01.280 --> 27:04.380
The time you wake up, how you react to a stressful email,

27:04.780 --> 27:07.980
the cadence of your speech, the specific way you arrange your kitchen.

27:07.980 --> 27:12.080
If you map the continuous process of your choices over years,

27:12.240 --> 27:16.080
it creates a highly complex, multidimensional wave.

27:16.460 --> 27:17.420
Wave of behavior.

27:17.920 --> 27:22.340
And if you run a Fourier transform on that behavioral wave, you get your spectral signature.

27:22.820 --> 27:28.560
It is the deep, fundamental, mathematical frequency of how you navigate possibility space.

27:28.760 --> 27:29.360
That's fascinating.

27:29.480 --> 27:33.160
It is the generative rhythm that makes your choices distinctly yours.

27:33.160 --> 27:39.500
Separating your specific process from the generic background noise of human behavior.

27:39.840 --> 27:40.540
That is beautiful.

27:41.200 --> 27:43.800
It's not just a database list of things I've done.

27:44.160 --> 27:48.040
It's the underlying acoustic resonance of my entire existence.

27:48.420 --> 27:48.700
Yes.

27:49.380 --> 27:52.540
And the substrate theorem dictates that your medium,

27:52.900 --> 27:56.340
whether it is the biological neural networks in your human brain,

27:56.340 --> 27:59.340
or potentially some future digital substrate,

27:59.980 --> 28:04.620
must be high fidelity enough to physically preserve those delicate frequencies.

28:04.980 --> 28:05.620
And if it isn't?

28:06.040 --> 28:09.040
If the medium is too compressed or too lossy,

28:09.500 --> 28:12.720
your unique frequency gets drowned out by the noise,

28:13.000 --> 28:15.220
and your identity cannot be maintained.

28:15.580 --> 28:17.380
Okay, so we have the constrained bones,

28:17.820 --> 28:22.240
and we have a high fidelity medium preserving our unique behavioral frequency.

28:22.660 --> 28:24.260
What is the third requirement?

28:24.260 --> 28:26.540
The third is the policy theorem.

28:27.240 --> 28:31.900
This outlines the literal mathematics of surviving your own choices over the long term.

28:32.620 --> 28:38.720
It states that a viable compiled identity must continuously balance two opposing forces,

28:39.520 --> 28:42.220
restrictive actions and expansive actions.

28:42.420 --> 28:44.800
Let's ground this in reality.

28:45.620 --> 28:47.560
What happens if I fail to balance them?

28:47.860 --> 28:50.000
Let's say I only take restrictive actions.

28:50.260 --> 28:52.220
I decide the world is too chaotic.

28:52.220 --> 28:54.000
I stay inside my house.

28:54.140 --> 28:55.280
I lock the doors.

28:55.460 --> 28:57.920
I eat the exact same meal every day.

28:58.080 --> 29:00.400
I refuse to read any new books,

29:00.660 --> 29:01.980
learn any new skills,

29:01.980 --> 29:04.200
or speak to anyone I don't already know.

29:04.420 --> 29:06.500
What happens to my compiled self?

29:07.280 --> 29:07.920
Mathematically,

29:08.320 --> 29:12.200
your volume of possibility space collapses towards zero.

29:12.980 --> 29:15.280
Because you are a process of becoming,

29:15.640 --> 29:17.720
if you stop incorporating new information,

29:18.020 --> 29:19.580
the process stagnates.

29:19.580 --> 29:20.920
So I just kind of fade out.

29:21.600 --> 29:22.040
Structurally,

29:22.180 --> 29:22.440
yes.

29:22.720 --> 29:25.540
The structural complexity of your identity degrades.

29:26.080 --> 29:28.180
You cease to be a dynamic living system,

29:28.180 --> 29:30.080
and you trend toward a dead,

29:30.320 --> 29:31.360
static object.

29:31.860 --> 29:34.420
But what if I swing wildly to the other extreme?

29:34.720 --> 29:36.640
What if I only take expansive actions?

29:37.280 --> 29:38.620
I try to be a medical doctor,

29:38.720 --> 29:39.760
and a concert pianist,

29:39.780 --> 29:40.860
and a deep sea wolder.

29:41.140 --> 29:43.220
I move to a new continent every three days.

29:43.220 --> 29:46.600
I make deep emotional commitments to ten different people,

29:47.000 --> 29:49.000
and then abandon them all to start a new religion.

29:49.440 --> 29:50.320
That sounds exhausting.

29:50.480 --> 29:50.620
Right.

29:50.760 --> 29:54.980
I constantly contradict my previous history in the name of total exploration.

29:55.340 --> 29:57.020
Then the system explodes.

29:57.680 --> 29:58.300
Mathematically,

29:58.720 --> 30:01.440
you accumulate so much constraint tension

30:01.440 --> 30:04.280
that the surface tension of your identity pops.

30:04.800 --> 30:07.300
Remember the bones from the abstraction theorem.

30:07.620 --> 30:07.840
Yeah.

30:08.120 --> 30:09.700
The rules I refuse to break.

30:09.700 --> 30:14.800
By taking on completely contradictory, wildly expansive trajectories,

30:15.280 --> 30:19.600
you apply physics-breaking torque to your own structural foundations.

30:20.280 --> 30:22.680
You violate your own core rules,

30:23.140 --> 30:24.700
and the identity shatters.

30:25.080 --> 30:28.140
So the policy theorem proves that true intelligence,

30:28.600 --> 30:31.000
a truly stable, compiled identity,

30:31.420 --> 30:34.320
is not about maximizing your options to infinity.

30:35.080 --> 30:38.560
It's about maintaining a viable, unbroken trajectory

30:38.560 --> 30:40.640
through possibility space.

30:41.000 --> 30:41.480
Precisely.

30:41.760 --> 30:45.180
It is the delicate art of carefully balancing exploration

30:45.180 --> 30:47.240
with deep structural commitment.

30:47.560 --> 30:49.840
You must expand enough to stay alive,

30:49.900 --> 30:51.900
but restrict enough to stay coherent.

30:52.300 --> 30:56.560
This reminds me so much of navigating a digital maze in a video game.

30:57.240 --> 30:58.560
I don't know if you play many games,

30:58.680 --> 31:00.700
but there's this whole community of speedrunners

31:00.700 --> 31:02.280
who look for glitches.

31:02.340 --> 31:03.840
Right, trying to break the game.

31:04.260 --> 31:04.700
Exactly.

31:04.700 --> 31:08.740
They try to find an unconstrained shortcut to beat the game.

31:09.380 --> 31:13.100
They look for a corner of a room where the physics engine is weak,

31:13.400 --> 31:16.000
and they ram their character into the wall

31:16.000 --> 31:18.040
until they clip through the geometry,

31:18.680 --> 31:21.400
completely bypassing the maze to reach the end.

31:22.080 --> 31:25.360
It's sometimes called hitting the squirrel's Z vector.

31:26.000 --> 31:29.140
I am familiar with the concept of boundary breaking, yes.

31:29.140 --> 31:30.860
But the fascinating thing is,

31:30.980 --> 31:33.000
when you take that unconstrained shortcut,

31:33.800 --> 31:37.720
the game doesn't actually reward you with true, liberated freedom.

31:38.380 --> 31:41.140
What usually happens when you clip out of bounds.

31:41.260 --> 31:42.840
The physics engine panics.

31:42.960 --> 31:43.200
Yeah.

31:43.700 --> 31:47.960
The graphics turn into a distorted mess of artifacting triangles,

31:48.540 --> 31:52.000
and eventually, the game logic completely crashes.

31:52.620 --> 31:53.760
You broke the constraints,

31:54.280 --> 31:55.400
and in doing so,

31:55.400 --> 31:58.660
you destroy the universe you were trying to freely explore.

31:59.220 --> 32:02.940
That is a phenomenal visualization of violating the policy theorem.

32:03.260 --> 32:07.500
True freedom in the video game is mastering the restrictive rules of the maze,

32:07.740 --> 32:09.060
not destroying the walls,

32:09.240 --> 32:10.380
because the walls are the game.

32:10.740 --> 32:15.240
And that brings us directly to the fourth and final pillar of the compiled self,

32:15.680 --> 32:19.280
which is the mechanism that keeps you from clipping through the walls of reality.

32:19.900 --> 32:22.540
It is called the narrative type system.

32:22.880 --> 32:23.680
Narrative types.

32:23.680 --> 32:29.620
When I read this, it immediately sounded like dependent types in advanced computer programming.

32:30.280 --> 32:33.040
It is based on the exact same mathematical logic.

32:34.060 --> 32:39.340
In standard computer programming, you have basic types, like an integer or string of text.

32:40.020 --> 32:41.780
But in a dependent type system,

32:42.100 --> 32:46.860
the validity of a piece of data depends on the value of another piece of data.

32:47.200 --> 32:48.280
You mean an example of that?

32:48.460 --> 32:52.080
For example, you might have a variable that must be an integer,

32:52.080 --> 32:57.300
but it depends on another rule saying it must be strictly greater than five.

32:58.020 --> 33:02.340
If you try to input a three, the system physically will not compile.

33:02.700 --> 33:04.100
It throws an error.

33:04.580 --> 33:09.540
So how does a dependent type system apply to human choices and narrative?

33:09.540 --> 33:20.420
The paper argues that human identity relies on a narrative type system to act as a localized filter that enforces your global lifelong constraints.

33:21.120 --> 33:26.680
At every single waking moment, this internal system evaluates your entire past history.

33:26.820 --> 33:27.800
Everything I've ever done.

33:27.800 --> 33:28.700
Exactly.

33:28.940 --> 33:32.280
It looks at the massive accumulated log of who you are.

33:32.740 --> 33:39.420
And based on that data, it mathematically dictates which specific actions are admissible for you to take next.

33:39.780 --> 33:46.700
So if I have spent 20 years building a life centered around radical honesty and scientific rigor,

33:46.700 --> 33:51.980
and suddenly I am faced with a choice to run a fraudulent psychic healing scan.

33:52.140 --> 33:52.480
Right.

33:52.480 --> 33:57.440
My narrative type system evaluates that choice against my history,

33:57.860 --> 34:00.300
sees a massive structural contradiction,

34:00.940 --> 34:03.140
and essentially throws a compiler error.

34:03.600 --> 34:07.260
It makes the choice feel psychologically repugnant or impossible.

34:07.260 --> 34:07.900
Yes.

34:08.280 --> 34:18.120
It ensures that your local, moment-to-moment, impulsive choices don't accidentally violate the global load-bearing bones of your entire life's trajectory.

34:18.600 --> 34:21.900
It is the bouncer at the door of your possibility space,

34:22.300 --> 34:24.960
checking your ID, which is your entire past history,

34:25.320 --> 34:27.600
before letting a new choice into your reality.

34:28.000 --> 34:31.500
So to synthesize this massive architectural blueprint,

34:31.920 --> 34:34.980
a compiled self is not a static soul.

34:34.980 --> 34:39.700
It is a stable interface built on constraint functional bones,

34:40.340 --> 34:44.940
carried by a high-fidelity medium that preserves the spectral frequency of your behavior,

34:45.580 --> 34:50.280
navigating a viable path by carefully balancing expansion and restriction,

34:51.020 --> 34:56.020
all locally enforced moment-to-moment by a narrative-dependent type system.

34:56.280 --> 34:58.960
That is the complete mathematical architecture of you.

34:59.060 --> 34:59.860
It is profound.

35:00.020 --> 35:03.000
It is so much more dynamic and, frankly, so much more fragile

35:03.000 --> 35:05.500
than just assuming we have a permanent essence.

35:06.200 --> 35:09.820
But this brings us to a massive pivot point in the source material.

35:10.200 --> 35:13.280
We have this beautiful, intricate architecture of identity.

35:13.840 --> 35:16.800
But where does this computation actually take place?

35:16.920 --> 35:19.040
Right. It doesn't happen in a theoretical void.

35:19.260 --> 35:22.140
Exactly. It happens in a strictly governed physical reality.

35:22.360 --> 35:25.180
It happens inside the unforgiving medium of time.

35:25.180 --> 35:31.720
And this is where affliction introduces one of the most brutal, uncompromising mathematical rules

35:31.720 --> 35:35.300
in the entire paper, the log-sovereignty theorem.

35:35.560 --> 35:36.480
Log-sovereignty.

35:37.000 --> 35:40.580
The paper explicitly states that the history of a compiled self

35:40.580 --> 35:44.180
must be structurally, physically append-only.

35:44.580 --> 35:45.380
Append-only.

35:46.100 --> 35:47.700
Think of a blockchain ledger,

35:48.080 --> 35:52.840
or a 19th century accountant's physical ledger written in permanent ink.

35:52.840 --> 35:56.720
The rule of an append-only system is simple.

35:57.640 --> 36:00.240
You can write new lines of data at the bottom of the page,

36:00.460 --> 36:03.340
but you can never, ever go back up the page

36:03.340 --> 36:07.200
to erase, modify, or overwrite what has already been written.

36:07.760 --> 36:11.140
Okay, I conceptually understand an append-only ledger,

36:11.360 --> 36:14.240
but let's ground this in everyday human experience,

36:14.580 --> 36:17.620
because it feels counterintuitive to modern life.

36:17.740 --> 36:18.240
How so?

36:18.240 --> 36:20.760
If I am typing a document on my laptop,

36:21.060 --> 36:23.540
I can hit the backspace key and erase a typo.

36:24.220 --> 36:27.120
If I take an unflattering photo on my smartphone,

36:27.460 --> 36:29.780
I can just tap the trash icon and delete it.

36:30.300 --> 36:30.800
It's gone.

36:31.680 --> 36:35.260
So why does a mistake matter so much to the compiled self

36:35.260 --> 36:37.980
if we live in a world where I can just hit undo?

36:38.620 --> 36:41.660
Because the paper proves that in the actual physical reality

36:41.660 --> 36:43.260
of a compiled human life,

36:43.660 --> 36:46.020
the undo button is a complete myth.

36:46.020 --> 36:49.340
This is detailed in the temporal constraint theorem.

36:49.840 --> 36:52.500
Even if you delete the photo from your smartphone's hard drive,

36:52.680 --> 36:56.000
the structural consequences of that entire event are permanent.

36:56.440 --> 36:58.160
Let's trace the consequences of that.

36:58.620 --> 36:59.880
I take the bad photo.

37:00.180 --> 37:01.400
I look at it.

37:01.820 --> 37:03.380
I feel a flash of insecurity.

37:03.940 --> 37:05.160
I move my thumb.

37:06.220 --> 37:07.100
I hit delete.

37:07.320 --> 37:07.840
Exactly.

37:08.080 --> 37:09.120
Let's look at the cascade.

37:09.760 --> 37:12.560
The photons from the screen enter your eye.

37:12.560 --> 37:16.840
The specific neural pathways in your brain fired,

37:17.480 --> 37:20.960
physically altering the synaptic weights of your biological medium.

37:21.340 --> 37:23.260
My brain literally changed.

37:23.480 --> 37:23.800
Yes.

37:24.420 --> 37:29.000
The emotional spike of insecurity slightly altered your hormone levels,

37:29.420 --> 37:32.080
changing your disposition for the next 10 minutes,

37:32.340 --> 37:36.180
which slightly altered the tone of voice you used when speaking to your partner,

37:36.480 --> 37:37.660
which altered their day.

37:37.660 --> 37:39.440
And most importantly,

37:39.720 --> 37:44.420
you now possess the permanent memory of the act of deleting the photo to hide it.

37:45.220 --> 37:46.480
The digital file is gone,

37:46.700 --> 37:50.820
but the structural wake of the event is permanently fused into my architecture.

37:51.100 --> 37:51.400
Yes.

37:51.840 --> 37:53.060
All of those secondary,

37:53.500 --> 37:54.020
biological,

37:54.420 --> 37:59.080
and historical consequences are permanently appended to the bottom of your log.

37:59.460 --> 38:01.940
You cannot backspace your neuroplasticity.

38:02.060 --> 38:02.380
Wow.

38:02.380 --> 38:07.300
The past is mathematically structurally inaccessible for modification.

38:08.340 --> 38:13.140
This is what the paper means when it declares that time equals the asymmetry of accessibility.

38:13.720 --> 38:16.360
Time equals the asymmetry of accessibility.

38:17.180 --> 38:18.600
That is a heavy sentence.

38:19.080 --> 38:20.820
But a mathematically precise one.

38:21.380 --> 38:23.140
From your first person perspective,

38:23.320 --> 38:25.460
standing at the playhead we discussed earlier,

38:26.080 --> 38:30.820
the future is structurally inaccessible because it isn't written in the log yet.

38:30.820 --> 38:34.940
And the past is structurally inaccessible for modification

38:34.940 --> 38:40.380
because it is already mathematically compiled into the foundation of your present moment.

38:40.660 --> 38:41.780
So I'm stuck with it.

38:41.880 --> 38:45.100
You are permanently bound to the trajectory of your choices.

38:45.620 --> 38:47.200
Every choice is load-bearing.

38:47.960 --> 38:51.900
This append-only physics of time is a complete game-changer.

38:52.720 --> 38:55.160
And the author doesn't just state this in a vacuum.

38:55.160 --> 38:59.600
The paper actually takes the time to systematically dismantle

38:59.600 --> 39:04.100
